[2] slightly disagree

while i understand where this sentiment comes from, i believe that labeling something as "wrong" solely based on its unnaturalness is a weak argument. just because something is not natural does not necessarily mean it is wrong or harmful. many useful and beneficial things in our lives are products of human innovation and technology, which are not natural but can contribute positively to society. instead of relying on the concept of "unnaturalness," i think it's more important to evaluate acts based on their consequences and whether they promote harm or well-being.
